Crucial Interview Tips
Why Sliding Window beats Map/Stack: Sliding window uses O(1) space, whereas Map/Stack approaches use O(n) space. If the array is all positives, always go for Sliding Window to impress the interviewer with space optimization.
The "Zero" Problem in Product: In the Max Product problem, a zero resets your product. Remember to handle it by either resetting your Kadane variables or using a "two-pass" approach (left-to-right and right-to-left).
The "At Most K" Trick: For problems like "Longest subarray with exactly K distinct elements," it is often easier to calculate (At Most K) - (At Most K-1) using a Sliding Window.
----------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Sliding Window (Two Pointers)
This is the most efficient approach O(n) time, but it only works if the condition is monotonic.
When to use: Longest/Shortest subarray where the sum/count <= k or >= k, and all elements are non-negative.
Mechanism: Expand the right pointer to find a valid window; shrink the left pointer to find the smallest valid (for shortest) or to stay within bounds (for longest).
Problems:
Longest Substring Without Repeating Characters
Minimum Size Subarray Sum
Max Consecutive Ones III
----------------------------------------------------------------------
2. Prefix Sum + HashMap
This approach "remembers" the past to solve the present.
When to use: Finding a subarray with an exact sum k (e.g., Sum = k), or where counts of two elements are equal.
Mechanism: Store prefixSum as the key and the index as the value.
For Longest: Only store the first occurrence of a sum.
For Shortest: Update the map with the latest occurrence.
Problems:
Subarray Sum Equals K
Contiguous Array
Path Sum III
----------------------------------------------------------------------
3. Prefix Sum + Monotonic Stack
This is the "pro" version for when things aren't simple.
When to use: Longest subarray with Sum > K or Sum < K when the array contains negative numbers.
Mechanism: Build a stack of prefix sum indices that are strictly decreasing. Then, iterate from the end of the array to find the widest "gap" that satisfies the inequality.
Problems:
Longest Well-Performing Interval
Maximum Width Ramp
Shortest Subarray with Sum at Least K
----------------------------------------------------------------------
4. Kadane’s Algorithm (Dynamic Programming)
When to use: Finding the Maximum Sum Subarray or Minimum Sum Subarray.
Mechanism: At each element, decide: "Should I start a new subarray here, or continue the previous one?"
current_max = max(arr[i], current_max + arr[i])
Problems:
Maximum Subarray
Maximum Sum Circular Subarray
Maximum Product Subarray
----------------------------------------------------------------------
5. Two-Pass / Deque (Sliding Window Maximum)
When to use: Problems involving the range (max - min) or a sliding window where you need the maximum/minimum element inside that window.
Mechanism: Use a Monotonic Queue (Deque) to keep track of the max/min element in O(1) as the window slides.
Problems:
Sliding Window Maximum
Longest Continuous Subarray With Absolute Diff Less Than or Equal to Limit
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
6. Binary Search on the Answer
When to use: When you can easily check if a subarray of length L exists that satisfies the condition.
Mechanism: If a subarray of length L works, does L+1 work? (Used often in "Smallest length such that sum >= K"). This is usually O(n \log n).
Problems:
Koko Eating Bananas
Split Array Largest Sum
Minimum Limit of Balls in a Bag
